Part II: Explanatory Data Analysis - Ford GoBike System

February 2019 Usage Patterns

This presentation summarizes key findings from the exploratory analysis of the Ford GoBike System data for February 2019. The analysis uncovers patterns in how the bike-sharing system is used across different user types, times, and locations in the San Francisco Bay Area.

Dataset Overview

The Ford GoBike System dataset contains trip data from the bike-sharing service in the San Francisco Bay Area for February 2019. Each record represents a single trip and includes information such as:

  • Trip duration
  • Start and end stations (location and IDs)
  • Start and end times
  • User type (Subscriber or Customer)
  • User demographics (birth year, gender)
  • Bike ID and usage program information

After data cleaning and filtering, we analyzed 182,995 bike trips from this period.

In[6]:
# Load the dataset and perform the same cleaning as in the exploratory notebook
df = pd.read_csv('201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv')

# Convert start_time and end_time to datetime
df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'])

# Create new features
df['trip_day_of_week'] = df['start_time'].dt.day_name()
df['trip_hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour
df['trip_duration_min'] = df['duration_sec'] / 60

# Define haversine function for distance calculation
def haversine(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2):
    # convert decimal degrees to radians 
    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(radians, [lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2])
    # haversine formula 
    dlon = lon2 - lon1 
    dlat = lat2 - lat1 
    a = sin(dlat/2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a)) 
    r = 6371 # Radius of earth in kilometers
    return c * r

# Calculate trip distance
df['trip_distance_km'] = df.apply(lambda row: haversine(
    row['start_station_longitude'], 
    row['start_station_latitude'],
    row['end_station_longitude'], 
    row['end_station_latitude']), axis=1)

# Calculate user age
df['member_birth_year'] = pd.to_numeric(df['member_birth_year'], errors='coerce')
current_year = 2019  # Data is from February 2019
df['member_age'] = current_year - df['member_birth_year']

# Filter out extreme values
df_filtered = df[(df['trip_duration_min'] <= 180) & (df['trip_duration_min'] >= 1)]

# Order days of week correctly
day_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
df_filtered['trip_day_of_week'] = pd.Categorical(df_filtered['trip_day_of_week'], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

# Display basic statistics
print(f"Total number of trips after filtering: {len(df_filtered):,}")
print(f"Number of unique stations: {df_filtered['start_station_id'].nunique()}")
print(f"Date range: {df_filtered['start_time'].dt.date.min()} to {df_filtered['start_time'].dt.date.max()}")

Key Finding 1: User Types Have Distinct Usage Patterns

The Ford GoBike system has two main user types:

  • Subscribers: Regular users with membership (89.3%)
  • Customers: Casual or one-time users (10.7%)

These user groups exhibit significantly different usage patterns in terms of trip duration, time of use, and purpose.

Key Finding 2: Temporal Usage Patterns Reveal Commuting Behavior

The bike-sharing system shows clear commuting patterns on weekdays, with distinct morning and evening peaks, while weekend usage is more evenly distributed throughout the day.

In[10]:
# Create weekday vs weekend column
df_filtered['is_weekend'] = df_filtered['trip_day_of_week'].isin(['Saturday', 'Sunday'])

# Count trips by hour for weekdays and weekends
weekday_trips = df_filtered[~df_filtered['is_weekend']].groupby('trip_hour').size()
weekend_trips = df_filtered[df_filtered['is_weekend']].groupby('trip_hour').size()

# Normalize by dividing by number of days
num_weekdays = df_filtered[~df_filtered['is_weekend']]['start_time'].dt.date.nunique()
num_weekends = df_filtered[df_filtered['is_weekend']]['start_time'].dt.date.nunique()
weekday_trips = weekday_trips / num_weekdays
weekend_trips = weekend_trips / num_weekends

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

plt.plot(weekday_trips.index, weekday_trips.values, marker='o', linewidth=3, 
         label='Weekdays (Mon-Fri)', color='#3274A1')
plt.plot(weekend_trips.index, weekend_trips.values, marker='o', linewidth=3, 
         label='Weekends (Sat-Sun)', color='#E1812C')

plt.title('Average Number of Trips by Hour: Weekdays vs. Weekends', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day (24-hour format)', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('Average Number of Trips', fontsize=16)
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

# Add annotations for key points
plt.annotate('Morning\ncommute\npeak', xy=(8, weekday_trips[8]), xytext=(8, weekday_trips[8]+1000),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05, width=1.5), ha='center')
plt.annotate('Evening\ncommute\npeak', xy=(17, weekday_trips[17]), xytext=(17, weekday_trips[17]+1000),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05, width=1.5), ha='center')
plt.annotate('Weekend\nleisure\nactivity', xy=(14, weekend_trips[14]), xytext=(14, weekend_trips[14]+1000),

plt.legend(fontsize=14)

Key Finding 3: User Type, Time, and Purpose are Interconnected

Combining user type and temporal patterns reveals how different users utilize the system for different purposes throughout the week.

# Create hour groups for easier visualization
df_filtered['hour_category'] = pd.cut(df_filtered['trip_hour'], 
                                     bins=[0, 6, 10, 15, 19, 24],
                                     labels=['Night (12AM-6AM)', 'Morning (6AM-10AM)', 
                                             'Midday (10AM-3PM)', 'Evening (3PM-7PM)', 
                                             'Night (7PM-12AM)'])

# Prepare data for plotting
user_hour_day = pd.crosstab(index=[df_filtered['user_type'], df_filtered['hour_category']],
                            columns=df_filtered['trip_day_of_week'])

# Reshape for easier plotting
user_hour_day_melt = user_hour_day.stack().reset_index()
user_hour_day_melt.columns = ['user_type', 'hour_category', 'day_of_week', 'count']

# Calculate the total for each group for percentage
user_hour_day_melt['total'] = user_hour_day_melt.groupby(['user_type', 'day_of_week'])['count'].transform('sum')
user_hour_day_melt['percentage'] = user_hour_day_melt['count'] / user_hour_day_melt['total'] * 100

# Plot 2: Scatter plot of duration vs distance with user type
sample_size = 10000  # Sample for better visualization
sample_df = df_filtered.sample(sample_size, random_state=42)
sns.scatterplot(data=sample_df, x='trip_distance_km', y='trip_duration_min', 
                hue='user_type', alpha=0.5, palette=['#3274A1', '#E1812C'], ax=ax2)

# Add trend lines for each user type
for user, color in zip(['Subscriber', 'Customer'], ['#3274A1', '#E1812C']):
    user_data = sample_df[sample_df['user_type'] == user]
    if len(user_data) > 0:
        x = user_data['trip_distance_km']
        y = user_data['trip_duration_min']
        z = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
        p = np.poly1d(z)
        ax2.plot(np.linspace(0, 8, 100), p(np.linspace(0, 8, 100)), 
                 color=color, linestyle='--', linewidth=3)
        
        # Calculate and display average speed
        avg_speed_kmh = (60 * x / y).median()
        ax2.text(6, p(6) + 5, f'{user}: {avg_speed_kmh:.1f} km/h', 
                 color=color, fontsize=13, bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.7))

ax2.set_title('Trip Duration vs Distance by User Type', fontsize=18)
ax2.set_xlabel('Trip Distance (km)', fontsize=16)
ax2.set_ylabel('Trip Duration (minutes)', fontsize=16)
ax2.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
ax2.set_xlim(0, 8)
ax2.set_ylim(0, 60)

Conclusions

Our analysis of the Ford GoBike System data reveals several important insights:

  1. Dual Purpose System: The bike-sharing system serves two distinct purposes:

    • A commuting tool for regular Subscribers (89% of users)
    • A leisure activity for one-time Customers (11% of users)

  2. Temporal Patterns: Clear usage patterns emerge across different times:

    • Weekday commute peaks in the morning (8-9 AM) and evening (5-6 PM)
    • More evenly distributed weekend leisure usage

  3. Trip Characteristics: User types show different behaviors:

    • Subscribers take shorter, faster, more direct trips (median: 8.5 min, 1.35 km)
    • Customers take longer, more leisurely trips (median: 13.5 min, 1.67 km)

  4. Station Popularity: Station usage varies based on:

    • Location (business district, residential area, tourist attraction)
    • Day of week and time of day
    • User demographic served (commuters vs. tourists)

These findings could help inform system optimization, such as bike rebalancing strategies, station capacity planning, and targeted marketing campaigns to different user segments.
